Doc Del,<br>
     Thanks for the advice, I'm glad you remembered to point that out.  As a elementary teacher, I have taught a number of Vietnamese children.  The day is really theirs.  I admire the journey the southeast asian people have made and their dedication to a our country.  Part of my father's duties in Vietnam were to train South Vietnamese Marine soldiers and build housing for them, so he speaks highly of them.  I sometimes wonder if we as Americans did the right thing by them.  Our soldiers fought a tough war, but in the end, Communist governments ended up in control of the nations involved.  My father often wonders what happened to the Vietnamese troops he served side by side with.  I hope they made it here.  In trying to understand the war, I have studied much on the post-1975 events, Pol Pot and the Year 0, the yellow rain in Laos etc.<br>
     This 30th I will direct our tribute to all those involved and we will try to discuss what has happened their.  Believe me it is tough for younger children, to understand (tough for me or my fellow teachers at times too!), but they can and should know about the suffering the southeast asians have and still endure.  Vietnam was their war as much as it was ours, a side that is mostly forgotten.  When I have discussed the war in the past with my sixth graders we talked about the culture/history of Cambodia, Vietnam and Laos.  I just wish more people knew it.  My salute to our vets is to let them know on the anniversary of the pull-out that they are not forgotten either.  Thanks for the advice Doc, I will take it to hearth and thanks for talking to someone who seeks to understand. 
